Federer entered the top 100 ranking for the first time on 20 September 1999 and started at the 1999 Marseille Open defeating the reigning champion of the 1998 French Open, Spaniard Carlos Moy√°. His first final came at the Marseille Open in 2000, where he lost to fellow Swiss Marc Rosset.[24] Federer won the 2001 Hopman Cup representing Switzerland, along with world No. 1 Martina Hingis.[25][26][27] The duo defeated the American pair of Monica Seles and Jan-Michael Gambill in the finals. Federer later said that his experience with Hingis "definitely helped me to become the player I am today."[28]
